WEBVTT

00:03.630 --> 00:05.359
(keypad beeping)

00:07.770 --> 00:09.704
*

00:37.570 --> 00:39.094
(doorbell rings)

00:39.140 --> 00:41.267
Hey, are you gonna
get that or...

00:41.300 --> 00:43.439
(TV playing quietly)

00:43.470 --> 00:45.631
Hey, Sherlock's asleep.

00:45.670 --> 00:47.774
I wasn't sure
if I should get the door.

00:49.650 --> 00:52.744
I'm Gwen-- you're
the companion, right?

00:52.780 --> 00:54.645
Yes.
(doorbell rings)

00:54.680 --> 00:57.649
Guess I should
go get dressed.

00:57.690 --> 00:59.248
(laughs)

00:59.290 --> 01:01.656
(doorbell rings)

01:07.700 --> 01:10.168
(doorbell rings)

01:10.200 --> 01:11.792
WOMAN: Sorry, I wasn't
sure if you wanted me

01:11.830 --> 01:13.138
to get...

01:13.170 --> 01:15.661
Oh, you're
not Sherlock.

01:15.700 --> 01:17.201
You're the companion, right?

01:17.240 --> 01:18.730
Yes.

01:18.770 --> 01:20.408
I'm Olivia.
It's nice to meet you.

01:20.440 --> 01:22.146
I think I just met your sister.

01:22.180 --> 01:24.148
Did she mention what time our
car servnce IS getting here?

01:24.180 --> 01:25.442
(doorbell rings)
No.

01:25.480 --> 01:26.811
You should get the door.

01:26.850 --> 01:28.875
There's crepes
downstairs if you want.

01:28.920 --> 01:32.287
Good morning.

01:32.320 --> 01:36.188
Well, if you must know, Watson,
the Lynch sisters and I enjoy

01:36.230 --> 01:37.549
a mutually beneficial
relationship.

01:37.590 --> 01:39.421
"If I must know?"
I didn't ask.

01:39.460 --> 01:41.291
I need to study the difference
between two specimens born

01:41.330 --> 01:42.888
into the world with exactly
the same genetic material.

01:42.930 --> 01:46.195
In the Lynches case,
there are seven major ones.

01:46.240 --> 01:47.491
And they get...

01:47.540 --> 01:49.838
I... didn't... ask.

01:49.870 --> 01:51.337
(doorbell rings)

01:51.370 --> 01:52.701
If that's for me,
I'm not here.

01:52.740 --> 01:53.877
I'm going back to bed,

01:55.740 --> 01:57.844
Good morning.

01:57.880 --> 01:59.916
Does, um,
Sherlock Holmes live here?

01:59.950 --> 02:01.372
I was referred here

02:01.420 --> 02:03.285
by an old colleague
of his in London.

02:03.320 --> 02:05.140
He said I might have
to try more than once.

02:05.190 --> 02:06.851
Good advice.
Would you please tell him

02:06.890 --> 02:08.812
that I need
to speak with him?

02:08.860 --> 02:10.555
Why don't you
tell him yourself.

02:15.530 --> 02:18.624
Casterly Rock Security.

02:18.670 --> 02:21.264
The world's foremost maker
of bank vaults.

02:21.300 --> 02:24.428
And you, Mr. Erlich, are the
president and head engineer.

02:24.470 --> 02:26.506
I am familiar with
your work. Crepe?

02:28.940 --> 02:32.148
Bye, Sherlock.

02:34.880 --> 02:38.316
If you know our work,
you know that

02:38.350 --> 02:40.818
we introduced a new flagship
product in 2009.

02:40.860 --> 02:43.283
The Leviathan.
Yes.

02:43.330 --> 02:46.959
The safe that you marketed
as impregnable.

02:47.000 --> 02:50.367
Did you people learn nothing
from the Titanic?

02:50.400 --> 02:52.231
Bye, Sherlock.

02:58.740 --> 03:01.573
Your company introduced a
supposedly unbreakable safe

03:01.610 --> 03:04.477
in 2009, and then paid
the price for your hubris

03:04.510 --> 03:08.674
when The Leviathan was plundered
within the calendar year.

03:08.720 --> 03:11.245
Thank you.

03:11.290 --> 03:14.214
The four men who robbed
that bank, they were brilliant.

03:14.260 --> 03:17.252
A once-in-a-lifetime assembly
of criminal talent.

03:17.290 --> 03:20.657
Now, eventually all four
were caught and convicted,

03:20.700 --> 03:22.395
but none of them talked.

03:22.430 --> 03:25.228
We did what we could to improve
the product, but the chance

03:25.270 --> 03:28.831
of another four criminals_
that bright collaborating again?

03:31.410 --> 03:36.438
The Svalbard Diamond Exchange
was robbed last night.

03:36.480 --> 03:39.449
They're missing
$40 million in stones.

03:39.480 --> 03:41.368
Stones protected
by your vault.

03:41.420 --> 03:44.947
The Leviathan has
a seven-figure price tag.

03:44.990 --> 03:47.686
If somebody finds out that
another one's been compromised

03:47.720 --> 03:50.655
and we don't know how,
we're done.

03:50.690 --> 03:54.854
Well, the police must be looking
into who robbed your vault.

03:54.900 --> 03:57.596
I take it the "how"
is where I come in?

03:57.630 --> 04:00.963
I think that there must have
been a fifth conspirator.

04:01.000 --> 04:03.400
Someone the other thieves
never told us about.

04:03.440 --> 04:05.465
Poppycock.

04:05.510 --> 04:06.875
The height of
intellectual vanity.

04:06.910 --> 04:08.571
If one group of people
can figure out

04:08.610 --> 04:09.975
how to get past your vault,

04:10.010 --> 04:11.671
so can a second...
No, you don't understand.

04:11.710 --> 04:14.349
We have six layers
of bleeding-edge security,

04:14.380 --> 04:15.916
redundancy at every step.

04:15.950 --> 04:17.440
And if a second group can,
so can a third.

04:17.490 --> 04:18.639
If you want to know the answer,

04:18.690 --> 04:19.918
just take me
to the diamond exchange.

04:19.960 --> 04:21.018
We'll talk fee
on the way,

04:21.060 --> 04:22.823
although I'm not sure I have

04:22.860 --> 04:25.749
a rate for a job that's only
gonna take an hour or two.

04:25.790 --> 04:27.894
HOLMES:
The security upstairs is

04:27.930 --> 04:29.659
rather rudimentary.

04:29.700 --> 04:31.759
I take it anything of value
is stowed in the vault,

04:31.800 --> 04:32.767
after hours.

04:32.800 --> 04:34.495
Mr. Erlich.

04:34.540 --> 04:35.859
The police said
that your consultant

04:35.900 --> 04:37.800
can't see the vault
till they're done.

04:37.840 --> 04:40.308
I'm also a consultant
with the NYPD, Mister...?

04:40.340 --> 04:42.649
Batonvert, David Batonvert.
I'm the floor manager here.

04:42.680 --> 04:44.079
I assure you I know
how to conduct myself

04:44.110 --> 04:45.646
at a crime scene, Mr. Batonvert.

04:45.680 --> 04:47.875
Your name_ means
"green stick" In French.

04:47.920 --> 04:49.478
Uh, yeah?

04:49.520 --> 04:52.751
So, you have a motion sensor

04:52.790 --> 04:55.418
embedded in the ceiling,
a light sensor on the wall.

04:55.460 --> 04:57.826
Cardboard box can take care
of the motion sensor.

04:57.860 --> 05:01.626
The light detector they would
mask with simple black tape.

05:01.660 --> 05:04.094
They made short work
of that lock.

05:04.130 --> 05:06.860
Body heat sensor in the ceiling
could be coated with hair spray,

05:06.900 --> 05:09.903
buy a little time,
which brings us to...

05:09.940 --> 05:12.477
the door itself, yes.

05:12.510 --> 05:14.774
She is beautiful, hmm.

05:14.810 --> 05:17.370
This lock is not pickable.

05:17.410 --> 05:19.048
That key is, what, a foot long?

05:19.080 --> 05:21.378
The tumblers are weighted
so they cannot be manipulated

05:21.420 --> 05:23.012
with a pick.

05:23.050 --> 05:24.642
You could, of course,

05:24.690 --> 05:27.659
put a tiny camera
on this fire extinguisher.

05:27.690 --> 05:28.782
If you knew
an excellent locksmith,

05:28.820 --> 05:30.526
you could provide
an image of the key,

05:30.560 --> 05:31.720
have it duplicated.

05:31.760 --> 05:34.524
Clever, but we
already knew that.

05:34.560 --> 05:37.859
Ten-digit access code?

05:37.900 --> 05:40.869
Yes, it's provided by
a random number generator

05:40.900 --> 05:41.935
that's hardwired
into the system.

05:41.970 --> 05:42.937
The code changes
every two minutes.

05:42.970 --> 05:44.506
Who has the code?

05:44.540 --> 05:46.679
It appears on a key file
that the owner carries.

05:46.710 --> 05:49.508
If you want to get in there,
he's got to read it to you.

05:49.550 --> 05:51.370
He's in Gstaad right now.

05:51.410 --> 05:52.946
He's had the fob on him
the whole time.

05:52.980 --> 05:54.811
You could attack
the random number generator,

05:54.850 --> 05:56.943
make it spit out a pattern,
so you could predict the code.

05:56.990 --> 05:59.379
The number generator
is working perfectly.

06:03.460 --> 06:06.520
I'm gonna need
a little time with this.

06:19.010 --> 06:21.001
(keypad beeping)

06:24.680 --> 06:26.841
What are you doing down here?

06:26.880 --> 06:28.575
Stress testing the keypad.

06:28.620 --> 06:31.111
You think there'd be some tell
in the keys themselves.

06:31.150 --> 06:32.913
No, I mean, what are you
still doing down here?

06:32.960 --> 06:34.712
You said you were gonna
be gone two hours.

06:34.760 --> 06:36.455
It's been all day.
Has it?

06:36.490 --> 06:38.128
How stubborn are you
gonna be about this?

06:38.160 --> 06:40.458
Uh, excuse me?
We're closing now.

06:40.500 --> 06:42.627
Green Stick, do you want
your diamonds back or not?

06:56.040 --> 06:58.873
(gasps)

06:58.910 --> 07:01.049
Oh, she thinks she's
a clever one, doesn't she?
Who's she?

07:01.080 --> 07:02.843
Her.
What time is it?

07:02.890 --> 07:04.482
She generates an ocean
of pure randomness,

07:04.520 --> 07:06.215
and she wants you
to just lose hope and drown

07:06.250 --> 07:09.219
in all those numbers,
but I can see the horizon line.

07:09.260 --> 07:10.488
I can tread water.

07:10.530 --> 07:12.054
Stop.

07:12.090 --> 07:14.092
It is 2:00 in the morning.

07:14.130 --> 07:15.893
You've been down here for
almost, what, 17 hours?

07:17.800 --> 07:20.030
I'm supposed to meet my mother
for brunch in the morning.

07:20.070 --> 07:22.607
Not spending the night
in a bank vault.
So, go then.

07:22.640 --> 07:24.198
I'm not gonna leave you
down here like this either.

07:24.240 --> 07:26.572
In A.A., they'd say
you're on a dry drunk.

07:26.610 --> 07:28.771
You're indulging in all
the obsessions of addiction

07:28.810 --> 07:30.846
without actually using drugs,
so are you gonna admit

07:30.880 --> 07:32.973
that you can't think your
way past that vault door

07:33.020 --> 07:35.079
or am I gonna have to
smash the fire alarm

07:35.120 --> 07:36.678
and get us both
dragged out of here?

07:36.720 --> 07:38.711
You're absolutely
right, Watson.

07:38.750 --> 07:40.786
I can sometimes disappear into
the rabbit hole of my psyche.

07:40.820 --> 07:42.014
Okay, good, then
you're ready to go.

07:42.060 --> 07:43.584
Would you mind terribly
if I just tried

07:43.630 --> 07:45.029
one more idea before we leave?
(groans)

07:45.060 --> 07:46.789
It'll only take a minute.
Fine.

07:48.560 --> 07:49.527
(glass shatters)

07:49.570 --> 07:50.764
What are you doing?!

07:50.800 --> 07:52.893
Oh, my God, put that down!

07:52.940 --> 07:54.794
Put that down!

07:57.710 --> 08:00.201
Before you say anything,

08:00.240 --> 08:03.107
I would like to remind you
that I'm holding an ax.

08:27.240 --> 08:28.969
Did you give the people
at Casterly Rock

08:29.000 --> 08:30.968
my cell phone number
as your contact info?

08:31.010 --> 08:33.103
Well, I didn't want
them to call me.

08:33.140 --> 08:35.677
Yeah, well, they're wondering
who took an ax to their vault.

08:35.710 --> 08:37.575
Apparently the repair bill's
gonna be huge.

08:37.610 --> 08:38.975
Cost of doing business.

08:39.010 --> 08:40.841
They'll get over it
when I figure this out.

08:40.880 --> 08:42.711
We need to figure out

08:42.750 --> 08:45.218
who broke into the safe;
that's the way that we'll learn

08:45.250 --> 08:46.979
how it happened.

08:47.020 --> 08:48.715
It wasn't an inside job.

08:48.760 --> 08:50.284
Everyone at Casterly
Rock who knew

08:50.330 --> 08:52.719
how to get into that
thing has given an alibi.

08:52.760 --> 08:54.728
And I can't see how
the original thieves

08:54.760 --> 08:56.091
would've needed
a fifth conspirator.

08:56.130 --> 08:58.690
The four of them had
all the tools they needed

08:58.730 --> 08:59.867
between them.

08:59.900 --> 09:02.698
No, obvious what happened.

09:02.740 --> 09:05.106
One of the original team
sold the recipe

09:05.140 --> 09:08.598
for breaching The Leviathan
to an outside party.

09:08.640 --> 09:10.676
That's obvious?

09:10.710 --> 09:13.019
When you've eliminated the
impossible, whatever remains,

09:13.050 --> 09:15.712
however improbable,
is the truth.

09:15.750 --> 09:17.911
And what's impossible here
is that you couldn't break

09:17.950 --> 09:20.089
into the safe, but
someone else could.

09:20.120 --> 09:23.829
In other worlds, you are the
smartest man in the world.

09:25.830 --> 09:28.151
Waiting for you to chime in
and say that's ridiculous.

09:28.200 --> 09:30.998
You'd think it would be
easy to get one of the four

09:31.030 --> 09:33.828
original team to admit that
they sold the secret on.

09:33.870 --> 09:35.599
But Carter Averill,

09:35.640 --> 09:37.631
the man who organized the heist
died in prison last year,

09:37.670 --> 09:40.878
and the other three have yet
to respond to my request

09:40.910 --> 09:42.309
for a visit.

09:42.340 --> 09:44.945
(phone ringing)

09:44.980 --> 09:47.210
You should answer that.

09:47.250 --> 09:49.047
Tell them it was
a necessary part of my process.

09:49.080 --> 09:50.980
What are my keys doing here?

09:51.020 --> 09:52.180
They weigh
the right amount.

09:52.220 --> 09:53.949
And enjoy brunch
with your mother.

09:53.990 --> 09:55.981
I hadn't realized
you were still so eager

09:56.020 --> 09:57.726
to impress her.

09:57.760 --> 09:59.625
You're dressed like _
you're gomg to a job InterVIew,

09:59.660 --> 10:01.651
not brunch with
a loved one.

10:08.100 --> 10:10.762
(speaking Mandarin)

10:10.810 --> 10:13.631
Okay, I was still
reading that.

10:13.680 --> 10:15.238
I told them to bring us
whatever's freshest.

10:15.280 --> 10:18.078
So, I'm in the cab

10:18.110 --> 10:20.317
on the way over,
and guess who I hear from.

10:20.350 --> 10:22.045
(phone ringing)

10:24.420 --> 10:25.785
Do you have to take that?

10:25.820 --> 10:27.185
No. Go on.

10:28.390 --> 10:29.982
Your brother called.

10:30.030 --> 10:32.123
He called me; do you know
how rare that is?

10:32.160 --> 10:35.357
I haven't spoken to Oren
in, what, two months?

10:35.400 --> 10:37.061
He's coming to the city.

10:37.100 --> 10:38.965
And he's
bringing Gabrielle.

10:39.000 --> 10:40.365
Wow.

10:40.400 --> 10:42.960
He tried to cut his trip short
in order to come back

10:43.010 --> 10:45.160
for dinner with us tomorrow
night, but It dIdn't work out.

10:45.210 --> 10:46.268
Wait, tomorrow night?

10:46.310 --> 10:47.800
Mm-hmm.

10:47.840 --> 10:49.171
Mom, you know about
my job, right?

10:49.210 --> 10:50.871
I mean, I can't just
leave my client alone.

10:50.910 --> 10:53.014
This is your brother, Joan.

10:53.050 --> 10:54.244
Can't your client just get

10:54.280 --> 10:55.747
a different babysitter
for tomorrow night?

10:55.780 --> 10:58.248
"Babysitter."
Okay, here we go.

10:58.290 --> 10:59.245
(phone ringing)

10:59.290 --> 11:00.814
I didn't mean it that way.

11:00.860 --> 11:03.226
You know, I'm just
gonna get that,

11:03.260 --> 11:05.319
_because it's
just gonna...
Mm.

11:05.360 --> 11:06.827
Hey, everything okay?

11:06.860 --> 11:08.054
HOLMES:
Excellent, actually.

11:08.100 --> 11:09.863
Don't come back
to the brownstone.

11:09.900 --> 11:11.868
Meet me at Sing Sing Prison
at 2:30.

11:11.900 --> 11:14.095
Why do you want me to meet you
at Sing Sing?

11:14.140 --> 11:15.698
Charles Briggs, the lock-pick

11:15.740 --> 11:17.002
from the original team
of thieves--

11:17.040 --> 11:18.860
he's agreed to sit down with us.

11:18.910 --> 11:20.207
Okay.

11:20.240 --> 11:22.105
Okay, I'll see you there.

11:22.140 --> 11:24.700
Sing Sing, the prison?

11:24.750 --> 11:26.968
(door buzzes)
BRIGGS:
You said you want to know

11:27.020 --> 11:28.874
how we got
into Leviathan.

11:28.920 --> 11:31.286
And you think
for some reason,

11:31.320 --> 11:34.756
even though I kept my mouth shut
during the trial,

11:34.790 --> 11:37.020
I'm going to tell you.

11:37.060 --> 11:39.028
You did agree to see me,

11:39.060 --> 11:40.948
which implies
you have a price.

11:41.000 --> 11:43.264
You're one of the
best lock-pickers

11:43.300 --> 11:45.165
in the world,

11:45.200 --> 11:48.294
and I collect_
expertise, Mr. Briggs,

11:48.340 --> 11:50.763
people to help me with
my consultancy work

11:50.810 --> 11:52.402
on an as-needed basis.

11:52.440 --> 11:57.173
I think I could find a use
for a mind as lively as yours.

11:57.210 --> 11:58.871
You want me to work
for the cops?

11:58.910 --> 12:01.174
I want to offer you a
chance to use your brain.

12:01.220 --> 12:02.983
I suspect

12:03.020 --> 12:04.817
it'll be the only
such offer you get

12:04.850 --> 12:06.340
for the rest of
your natural life.

12:09.960 --> 12:12.451
How did you get past
The Leviathan door,

12:12.490 --> 12:14.754
and who did you
sell your secret to?

12:16.560 --> 12:20.337
I don't know exactly
how we got in.

12:20.370 --> 12:22.338
We were specialized.

12:22.370 --> 12:25.100
I was responsible for getting
past the outer door.

12:25.140 --> 12:27.074
Averill figured out the code,

12:27.110 --> 12:29.328
but never told the rest of us
how he did it.

12:29.380 --> 12:32.247
After he got sick, he told me
someone got in touch with him.

12:32.280 --> 12:34.817
Averill said this guy wanted
to know how he did it,

12:34.850 --> 12:36.078
and he was willing to pay.

12:36.120 --> 12:38.884
If you're saying
that somebody else

12:38.920 --> 12:40.410
broke into one
of those vaults,

12:40.460 --> 12:42.485
my guess is Carter saw
an opportunity

12:42.520 --> 12:45.159
to get a little money
for his family before he died,

12:45.190 --> 12:46.953
told the guy his secret.

12:47.000 --> 12:48.228
Who was it?

12:48.260 --> 12:49.921
I only know an alias.

12:53.000 --> 12:57.300
Even if you never find this guy,
which you won't...

12:58.610 --> 13:00.430
...is that enough
to land me this gig?

13:03.350 --> 13:06.103
The guy who Averill said
got in touch with him,

13:06.150 --> 13:09.119
everyone just calls him...

13:09.150 --> 13:11.584
Le Chevalier.

13:11.620 --> 13:13.417
WATSON:
So let me get this straight.

13:13.460 --> 13:14.859
This Le Chevalierguy,
he's a thief

13:14.890 --> 13:16.312
who's allegedly stolen

13:16.360 --> 13:18.248
an original copy
of Shakespeare's first folio,

13:18.290 --> 13:20.019
_a collection _
of anCIent Greek coms...

13:21.930 --> 13:24.262
And no one can give us
a description of him?

13:24.300 --> 13:28.066
No one knows if he's European,
American, a leprechaun.

13:28.100 --> 13:29.533
You're making a point
of some kind.

13:29.570 --> 13:31.128
Sounds like a fairy tale.

13:31.170 --> 13:32.899
Well, some
people think so.

13:32.940 --> 13:34.498
But all five robberies
attributed to Le Chevalier

13:34.540 --> 13:36.098
remain unsolved.

13:36.140 --> 13:38.005
And you asked Charles Briggs
for the name of the man

13:38.050 --> 13:39.915
who bought the secret,
and he gives you a legend,

13:39.950 --> 13:41.349
a man who might not
even exist.

13:41.380 --> 13:42.938
You know,
this is a snipe hunt.

13:42.990 --> 13:44.309
Briggs said it himself.

13:44.350 --> 13:46.318
No one's ever even _come close
to finding him.

13:46.350 --> 13:47.851
You're forgetting
one thing, Watson.

13:47.890 --> 13:49.482
I've never gone
looking for him.

13:49.520 --> 13:50.953
WATSON:
This painting was stolen

13:50.990 --> 13:53.026
the same night
that the Aster Museum

13:53.060 --> 13:54.391
finally unveiled
it to the public.

13:54.430 --> 13:56.022
Now, most people think
it was Le Chevalier.

13:56.060 --> 13:58.062
If he's real,
this guy's got style.

13:58.100 --> 13:59.419
This man is real.

