what she does, isn't it?

27:24.410 --> 27:25.809
"Sober companion."

27:25.840 --> 27:27.671
When I first heard
that term,

27:27.710 --> 27:30.201
I couldn't imagine what it
entailed, and I'm an addict.

27:30.240 --> 27:33.073
(laughter)

27:33.110 --> 27:35.340
She practices quite a
unique specialty, your daughter.

27:35.380 --> 27:37.348
She rebuilds lives
from the ground up.

27:37.380 --> 27:41.089
You can measure her success
in careers restored.

27:41.120 --> 27:46.319
In my case, criminals
caught and in lives saved.

27:46.360 --> 27:48.055
Interesting.

27:48.100 --> 27:50.091
Never thought of it like that.

27:50.130 --> 27:51.324
Of course you haven't.

27:51.370 --> 27:53.099
You've raised
a modest daughter.

27:53.130 --> 27:54.267
She would never
say such a thing.

27:54.300 --> 27:56.268
Shall we order?

27:56.300 --> 28:00.703
I hear the rabbit
is a-ma-zmg.

28:02.380 --> 28:04.200
I know you're gonna
blow this off,

28:04.250 --> 28:07.003
but I'm gonna say it
anyway: thank you.

28:07.050 --> 28:11.146
I've never been able to make
my family understand What I do.

28:11.190 --> 28:14.353
Yes, well, I meant very
little of What I said.

28:14.390 --> 28:16.881
There's the blowing-off part.

28:16.920 --> 28:18.353
I know my audience.

28:18.390 --> 28:23.760
I simply told them What
they wanted to hear.

28:23.800 --> 28:25.290
They're nice people,
your family,

28:25.330 --> 28:29.938
but they are, at their
core, conventional.

28:29.970 --> 28:31.835
You make an effort to
appearconvenbonaL

28:31.870 --> 28:36.170
but I know, Watson, you share
my love of all that is bizarre

28:36.210 --> 28:39.179
and outside the humdrum
routine of ordinary life.

28:39.210 --> 28:41.314
Your family Will never
understand this,

28:41.350 --> 28:44.080
so I gave them some words
that they would understand.

28:47.960 --> 28:49.916
What?

28:49.960 --> 28:51.325
I'm just curious

28:51.360 --> 28:53.521
_as to who Justin Guthrie_
might have collaborated With

28:53.560 --> 28:55.323
to rob the
diamond exchange.

28:55.360 --> 28:57.920
I've been sifting through
his phone in my downtime.

28:57.970 --> 29:00.791
That's the dead guy's phone?
Isn't that evidence?

29:00.840 --> 29:03.195
Yeah, well, I will give it
back When I'm finished.

29:03.240 --> 29:06.368
He stored three phone numbers
in his notes section.

29:06.410 --> 29:08.537
Each one has just a first name
next to it:

29:08.580 --> 29:10.036
Jeremy, Amelie, Alex.

29:10.080 --> 29:12.298
These are the names
of three people

29:12.350 --> 29:14.272
with Whom he served
on the jury.

29:14.320 --> 29:16.140
So they kept in touch.

29:16.180 --> 29:18.341
Have you served
jury service?

29:18.390 --> 29:20.449
Did you have
any desire

29:20.490 --> 29:24.449
to see those people
again when it was over?

29:26.460 --> 29:30.328
(opera music playing loudly)

29:32.030 --> 29:33.258
It's 3:00 in the morning!

29:33.300 --> 29:35.097
(volume decreases)

29:35.140 --> 29:37.199
It's nearly finished.
Don't turn it down.

29:37.240 --> 29:38.969
I'm basking.

29:39.010 --> 29:40.204
(volume increases)

29:40.240 --> 29:41.969
Can't you bask
in the morning?

29:42.010 --> 29:42.977
(music stops)

29:43.010 --> 29:45.149
It's this case, Watson.

29:45.180 --> 29:47.842
It_ renews one's_ faith
in the profe55ion.

29:47.880 --> 29:51.247
It's _a life of boundless
surprises, detective work.

29:51.290 --> 29:54.054
Do I have to find you
a drug test?

29:54.090 --> 29:57.218
These are the four men Who broke

29:57.260 --> 29:59.478
into The Leviathan
in 2010.

29:59.530 --> 30:01.953
Now, we've already met
Charles Briggs, lock-pick

30:02.000 --> 30:03.422
and locksmith extraordinaire.

30:03.460 --> 30:05.462
This is Vance Paulson.

30:05.500 --> 30:07.320
He_was the
in5ide man.

30:07.370 --> 30:09.292
The late Carter Averill,

30:09.340 --> 30:11.399
organizer of the crime,
genius.

30:11.440 --> 30:13.135
He mastered everything from
computer coding

30:13.170 --> 30:15.331
to surveillance software.

30:15.380 --> 30:20.147
And, finally, David Retts,
PhD in electrical engineering.

30:20.180 --> 30:22.978
Nothing about this is making me
want to bask.

30:23.020 --> 30:24.385
I haven't got
to the good bit yet.

30:24.420 --> 30:26.217
We already know

30:26.250 --> 30:28.013
that Justin _Guthrie's
programming skills

30:28.060 --> 30:32.281
allowed him to perform much the
same function as Carter Averill.

30:32.330 --> 30:35.549
Now _let's meet
some of his fellow jurors.

30:35.600 --> 30:40.299
Alex Wilson worked as
an electrical engineer

30:40.330 --> 30:44.039
until his employer forced
early retirement on him.

30:44.070 --> 30:45.298
Jeremy Lopez,

30:45.340 --> 30:47.205
son of a locksmith.

30:47.240 --> 30:51.643
Paid his way through school
by plying his father's trade.

30:51.680 --> 30:54.240
So you're saying that Justin
Guthrie committed this robbery

30:54.280 --> 30:55.941
with other members of the jury?

30:55.980 --> 30:57.277
Probably started as a joke.

30:57.320 --> 30:59.288
Jurors spend
a lot of time together.

30:59.320 --> 31:01.117
Lots of idle chitchat, hmm?

31:01.160 --> 31:03.958
They noted that between them,
they had the same skill set

31:03.990 --> 31:06.185
as the thieves
they were trying.

31:06.230 --> 31:08.448
Once Justin Guthrie spotted
the coded programming language,

31:08.500 --> 31:10.149
things turned serious.

31:10.200 --> 31:11.622
They realized
they'd been handed the recipe

31:11.670 --> 31:13.194
for making millions of dollars.

31:13.230 --> 31:16.358
So, who was the inside man?

31:16.400 --> 31:18.607
This is Amelie Widomski,

31:18.640 --> 31:21.473
a homemaker
from Roosevelt Island.

31:21.510 --> 31:24.604
Icouldn't make any sense
of it until I noticed

31:24.650 --> 31:27.346
that she'd written her maiden
name on some paperwork.

31:27.380 --> 31:30.042
Amelie Widomski was born
"Amelie Batonvert."

31:30.080 --> 31:31.047
Green Stick.

31:31.090 --> 31:33.217
The manager of

31:33.250 --> 31:37.482
the Svalbard Diamond Exchange
is her brother.

31:37.520 --> 31:40.125
Whether he was in on it
or whether she just used

31:40.160 --> 31:42.492
the family connection to gain
access during working hours,

31:42.530 --> 31:45.624
these are the four people
who robbed

31:45.670 --> 31:47.968
the Svalbard Diamond Exchange
two days ago.

31:48.000 --> 31:52.107
And one of them is killing
the others to keep the proceeds.

31:52.140 --> 31:53.937
GREGSON: Okay, ten jurors,
two alternates.

31:53.980 --> 31:55.936
The only surviving juror
we couldn't find is Alex Wilson.

31:55.980 --> 31:57.379
That's the engineer.

31:57.410 --> 31:59.549
You think he has something
to do with this, right?

31:59.580 --> 32:01.411
So, assuming you're right
about what happened,

32:01.450 --> 32:03.111
he's probably in the wind.

32:03.150 --> 32:05.038
Seems like
he could be our guy.

32:05.090 --> 32:06.341
Maybe, but I believe

32:06.390 --> 32:08.950
our killer is standing
in that room.

32:08.990 --> 32:10.355
That man is named
Jeremy Lopez.

32:10.390 --> 32:12.688
Even from here, you can
see his face is injured.

32:12.730 --> 32:14.357
You think Justin Guthrie
did that to him?

32:14.400 --> 32:15.697
Should be easy enough
to find out.

32:15.730 --> 32:17.197
(door opens)

32:17.230 --> 32:19.528
Ladies and gentlemen, um,

32:19.570 --> 32:22.437
so I'd like to start
by thanking you all

32:22.470 --> 32:24.062
for fulfilling your civic duty.

32:24.110 --> 32:27.364
The justice system called,
12 of you answered. Yes.

32:27.410 --> 32:29.401
Unfortunately, it seems that

32:29.440 --> 32:33.171
four of your number have become
criminals themselves,

32:33.210 --> 32:34.711
and one of those four

32:34.750 --> 32:37.116
is now a murderer.

32:38.490 --> 32:40.219
Shocking, I know.

32:40.250 --> 32:42.115
But we have
obtained a sample

32:42.160 --> 32:43.616
of the murderer's blood.

32:43.660 --> 32:45.753
Now it's a simple case
of comparing your DNA

32:45.790 --> 32:49.328
to that sample,
and we'll have our killer.

32:49.360 --> 32:52.158
Okay, you can start.

32:53.430 --> 32:55.295
HOLMES:
Please, bear in mind,

32:55.340 --> 32:57.467
we cannot force you
to give samples.

32:57.500 --> 32:59.058
But you've already
demonstrated

32:59.110 --> 33:00.634
your civic-mindedness
by serving as jurors,

33:00.670 --> 33:03.605
and I'm sure that the innocent
amongst you Will relish

33:03.640 --> 33:05.403
the chance to help
catch a murderer.

33:06.810 --> 33:07.777
If, however,
you recently

33:07.810 --> 33:09.675
did murder Justin Guthrie,

33:09.720 --> 33:12.041
you certainly should not
offer a sample.

33:12.090 --> 33:13.409
Uh, that would be folly.

33:18.490 --> 33:20.355
Everything all right, Mr. Lopez?

33:24.570 --> 33:26.720
Fine, fine.

33:28.370 --> 33:29.689
All right, everyone,

33:29.740 --> 33:31.139
you can go now.

33:31.170 --> 33:32.762
Thank you very much
for your time.

33:42.250 --> 33:44.081
make sure they
don't try to flee.

33:44.120 --> 33:46.486
Maybe he gave us that sample
because he knew if he didn't,

33:46.520 --> 33:48.488
we'd know
it was him.
(scoffs)

33:48.520 --> 33:50.681
I know. He seemed
pretty confident.

33:50.720 --> 33:53.086
Why would a killer just
hand off his DNA like that?

33:53.130 --> 33:54.222
I don't believe he would.

33:54.260 --> 33:55.727
BELL:
Captain.

33:55.760 --> 33:58.627
We just heard from an officer
in Irvington, New Jersey.

33:58.670 --> 34:00.422
Guy saw our BOLO
on Alex Wilson.

34:00.470 --> 34:02.768
This cop swears he saw Wilson
couple days ago.

34:02.800 --> 34:04.438
Gave us an address.

34:04.470 --> 34:06.131
We need to find him.

34:06.170 --> 34:08.377
I may have been wrong
about Jeremy Lopez,

34:08.410 --> 34:10.503
and I doubt Amelie Widomski
could throw a man

34:10.540 --> 34:13.577
out of a window,
so if Lopez is not our man,

34:13.610 --> 34:15.669
then Alex Wilson must be.

34:17.550 --> 34:18.517
(knocks)

34:18.550 --> 34:20.245
NYPD! Open up!

34:20.290 --> 34:21.518
(knocks)

34:21.560 --> 34:23.516
Let's go.
Open up or we're coming in.

34:23.560 --> 34:26.529
(flies buzzing)

34:26.560 --> 34:29.449
Detective, uh,
I'm concerned there's no need

34:29.500 --> 34:31.661
to look for Mr. Wilson inside.

34:31.700 --> 34:33.520
Not with this many
coffin flies around.

34:33.570 --> 34:35.128
Coffin flies?

34:35.170 --> 34:38.662
Small, humpbacked members
of the Phoridae family.

34:38.710 --> 34:40.337
They feed on decaying corpses.

34:40.370 --> 34:42.429
They're congregating
on this cardboard.

34:42.480 --> 34:45.699
(flies buzzing)

34:53.890 --> 34:55.687
Looks like he's been
dead at least two days.

34:55.720 --> 34:58.723
He didn't kill
Justin Guthrie yesterday.

35:05.300 --> 35:06.790
Oh, good, you're back.

35:06.830 --> 35:08.730
We just got the preliminary
DNA results

35:08.770 --> 35:10.761
back from
Justin Guthrie's apartment.

35:10.800 --> 35:14.804
It doesn't match Jeremy Lopez,
it doesn't match Alex Wilson.

35:14.840 --> 35:19.209
It belongs to an Army chaplain
by the name of Audrey Higuerra.

35:19.250 --> 35:21.468
What's her connection
to the jury?

35:21.520 --> 35:23.715
As far as we know,
she doesn't have one.

35:23.750 --> 35:25.240
HOLMES:
Seems rather noble,

35:25.290 --> 35:27.508
this Audrey Higuerra,
doesn't she?

35:27.550 --> 35:29.211
Very noble indeed.

35:29.260 --> 35:30.659
I don't like her.

35:30.690 --> 35:32.658
Is that because she's a chaplain
or because she has

35:32.690 --> 35:34.294
a "Habitat For Humanity" sticker
in her window?

35:34.330 --> 35:36.491
I don't like her
because she doesn't fit.

35:36.530 --> 35:38.919
It was a beautiful theory,
not a hair out of place.

35:38.970 --> 35:41.632
The first robbery, the team
of jurors-turned-criminals

35:41.670 --> 35:44.400
who turned on each other
like a pack of rabid dogs.

35:44.440 --> 35:45.862
But this Audrey
Higuerra--

35:45.910 --> 35:47.832
she doesn't have any
connection to these people.

35:47.870 --> 35:49.701
She doesn't
fit anywhere.

35:49.740 --> 35:52.504
Well, we found her blood in
Justin Guthrie's apartment.

35:52.550 --> 35:53.903
And someone once said

35:53.950 --> 35:55.679
once you've eliminated
the impossible,

35:55.720 --> 35:58.484
Whatever remains, no matter
how improbable, is the truth.

35:58.520 --> 35:59.839
Sounds like a Windbag.

36:01.990 --> 36:04.379
I don't see anything here
that supports the idea

36:04.430 --> 36:06.182
that she was
a murderer.

36:06.230 --> 36:07.185
HOLMES:
Quite the opposite.

36:07.230 --> 36:08.857
IfI could attribute

36:08.900 --> 36:13.360
three miracles to her, I would
nominate her for sainthood.

36:13.400 --> 36:16.597
Yeah, looks like she's got the
caring for the sick part down.

36:16.640 --> 36:20.360
She nursed her sister
through cancer.

36:20.410 --> 36:24.506
So, not only is Audrey Higuerra
not to be found in her own home,

36:24.550 --> 36:25.903
she's not even in the country.

36:25.950 --> 36:27.679
We just found her calendar.

36:27.710 --> 36:30.941
Turns out, she was deployed
to Kabul a couple weeks ago.

36:30.980 --> 36:32.516
That can't be.

36:32.550 --> 36:34.381
We just found a fresh
blood sample, hers,

36:34.420 --> 36:35.887
in Justin Guthrie's
apartment yesterday.

36:35.920 --> 36:37.649
We're waiting
on the Army to confirm

36:37.690 --> 36:39.521
that she's posted overseas,
but, I mean, look around.

36:39.560 --> 36:41.790
Does it look like anyone's
been here recently?

36:41.830 --> 36:43.491
Can I take back
everything I said

36:43.530 --> 36:44.929
about eliminating
the impossible?

36:44.970 --> 36:46.267
Why would you want to do that?

36:46.300 --> 36:47.267
Because Audrey Higuerra's sister

36:47.300 --> 36:48.494
died of leukemia.

36:48.540 --> 36:50.929
And then once she was gone,
Audrey did

36:50.970 --> 36:53.268
everything she could to help
people with the same disease.

36:53.310 --> 36:55.369
I used to see this at the
hospital all the time.

36:55.410 --> 36:56.934
They give them
to bone marrow donors.

36:58.310 --> 37:00.505
HOLMES: Do you still
have a police detail

37:00.550 --> 37:01.812
following Jeremy Lopez?

37:01.850 --> 37:04.444
We called it off
when the DNA results came back.

37:04.490 --> 37:06.981
You need to find him,
bring him in immediately.

37:15.360 --> 37:16.793
I don't know
Why I'm back here.

37:16.830 --> 37:18.525
I already gave
you people my DNA.

37:18.570 --> 37:20.424
Yeah, we had a little
problem with that.

37:20.470 --> 37:22.495
Something went wrong
with one of the swabs.

37:22.540 --> 37:25.964
If it's not too much trouble,
we'd like to get a blood sample.

37:26.010 --> 37:27.762
It's a cleaner read.

37:27.810 --> 37:29.903
I've already been very helpful.

37:29.940 --> 37:31.339
Generous, even.

37:31.380 --> 37:32.540
But, honestly,
I don't like needles.

37:32.580 --> 37:34.343
I don't see why I should...

37:34.380 --> 37:35.540
HOLMES:
There they are.

37:35.580 --> 37:36.717
The e_vasions_
and rhetorical curlicues

37:36.750 --> 37:38.342
of a man with something to hide.

37:38.390 --> 37:39.709
I don't have anything to hide.

37:39.750 --> 37:42.617
You had leukemia; is
that correct, Jeremy?

37:42.660 --> 37:44.321
Yeah. Five years ago.

37:44.360 --> 37:45.622
I'm better now.
Good.

37:45.660 --> 37:46.820
And you're better because of

37:46.860 --> 37:48.452
a bone marrow
transplant, right?

37:48.500 --> 37:50.855
Did you know that one
of the side effects

37:50.900 --> 37:53.869
of a bone marrow transplant
is that your body

37:53.900 --> 37:56.869
begins to manufacture cells
that bear the DNA of your donor?

37:56.900 --> 37:58.458
Right.

37:58.510 --> 37:59.932
And bone marrow
manufactures blood.

37:59.970 --> 38:02.837
So you know that every
recipient of a transplant

38:02.880 --> 38:04.745
walks around with the
DNA of their donor

38:04.780 --> 38:06.441
coursing through
their veins.

38:06.480 --> 38:10.576
But the DNA in your skin,
your hair, your saliva,

38:10.620 --> 38:12.941
that's all your own.

38:12.990 --> 38:15.550
The blood that we found at
Justin Guthrie's apartment,

38:15.590 --> 38:17.979
it bears the DNA
of Audrey Higuerra,

38:18.020 --> 38:19.829
but it came
from your body.

38:19.860 --> 38:22.420
You knew that you could
give us a saliva sample,

38:22.460 --> 38:24.496
because the DNA
wouldn't match the blood

38:24.530 --> 38:26.361
that we found at
the crime scene.

38:26.400 --> 38:31.633
I cannot believe that you are
dragging my illness into this.

38:31.670 --> 38:34.878
You stole $40 million, and then
you murdered two people.

38:37.040 --> 38:38.109
I'm leaving.

38:38.140 --> 38:39.471
Don't call me.

38:39.510 --> 38:40.772
Don't expect me
to cooperate.

38:40.810 --> 38:44.041
Oh, we don't need
your cooperation.

38:46.050 --> 38:47.779
What's that?

38:47.820 --> 38:49.014
Court order.

38:49.060 --> 38:51.756
Compels you to give us
a blood sample.

38:51.790 --> 38:52.779
HOLMES:
We neglected to mention

38:52.830 --> 38:53.785
that we had that

38:53.830 --> 38:54.899
when we first came in.

38:54.930 --> 38:55.919
Yes.

38:55.960 --> 38:57.655
Well, we just didn't want

38:57.700 --> 39:00.021
to deny ourselves the pleasure
of watching you squirm.

39:00.070 --> 39:02.493
You give us
enough to arrest

39:02.540 --> 39:05.703
Amelie Widomski for her part
in the robbery, and who knows?

39:05.740 --> 39:09.574
Maybe a parole board
will see you before you're dead.

39:18.590 --> 39:20.717
Such a shame.

39:20.750 --> 39:23.719
Those bottles cost $500 apiece.

39:23.760 --> 39:25.955
You'd think if they wanted
to thank me with champagne,

39:25.990 --> 39:30.552
they'd go to the trouble
of finding out if I drink first.

39:30.600 --> 39:32.488
Have a glass if you like.

39:32.530 --> 39:35.465
You figured out Audrey Higuerra
was a bone marrow donor.

39:35.500 --> 39:38.037
Pretty sure that's
not a good idea.

39:38.070 --> 39:40.709
Is the smell
gonna bother you?

39:40.740 --> 39:45.575
I suppose being proven right
is the best gift of all.

39:45.610 --> 39:46.577
Hmm.

39:46.610 --> 39:47.907
There was no genius

39:47.950 --> 39:50.475
who independently
cracked The Leviathan.

39:50.520 --> 39:52.715
It was a question
of copying the original team.

39:52.750 --> 39:53.887
Ah.

39:53.920 --> 39:55.615
So that means you still might be

39:55.660 --> 39:57.013
the smartest person
in the world.

39:57.060 --> 39:58.482
I would never suggest that.

39:58.530 --> 39:59.758
Really?

39:59.790 --> 40:01.451
I think that's the first time

40:01.500 --> 40:03.195
I've ever heard you say
anything remotely modest.

40:03.230 --> 40:04.925
It's not modesty.

40:04.970 --> 40:07.461
There's just no reliable way
to test the hypothesis.

40:07.500 --> 40:08.990
(doorbell rings)

40:09.040 --> 40:11.804
Triplets?

40:20.780 --> 40:23.010
Mom?

40:23.050 --> 40:25.086
I know I'm not
supposed to come see you

40:25.120 --> 40:26.917
While you're out on a job,

40:26.950 --> 40:29.487
but you did give me your card
the other night.

40:29.520 --> 40:31.488
I was hoping
to talk to my daughter.

40:31.530 --> 40:33.088
HOLMES: _
Mm, please, come in.

40:33.130 --> 40:36.622
Thank you.

40:36.660 --> 40:39.697
I'll leave you
two to chat.

40:43.670 --> 40:47.504
It's, uh... nice.

40:47.540 --> 40:49.201
I've never seen
anything like it,

40:49.240 --> 40:53.040
but it seems like, uh,
it suits your client.

40:53.080 --> 40:55.776
So, you just wanted to come over
here to see Where I'm staying?

40:55.820 --> 40:59.938
I know you think that I
don't like your new career.

40:59.990 --> 41:02.515
To put it mildly.

41:02.560 --> 41:04.084
You're right, I don't like it.

41:04.120 --> 41:07.180
But not for the reasons
that you think.

41:07.230 --> 41:09.255
I'm not happy
that you're a sober companion

41:09.300 --> 41:11.188
because it never seems
to make you happy.

41:11.230 --> 41:13.596
How do you know
what makes me happy?

41:13.630 --> 41:16.030
I know because
you're my daughter.

41:18.070 --> 41:21.233
(sighs)

41:23.840 --> 41:27.776
After you left medicine,
after what happened with Liam,

41:27.810 --> 41:29.778
I've always thought
that this job

41:29.820 --> 41:33.711
was something that
you picked out of...

41:33.750 --> 41:36.514
I don't know, out
of a sense of duty.

41:36.560 --> 41:39.085
When you came to dinner
the other night,

41:39.130 --> 41:41.894
when the two of you talked
about Sherlock's work,

41:41.930 --> 41:45.889
I saw something
in you.

41:45.930 --> 41:48.023
There was a spark.

41:48.070 --> 41:50.595
A sense of
eXCItement.

41:50.640 --> 41:53.165
_ I haven't seen that
in you in a long time.

41:53.210 --> 41:56.236
You like
what he does.

41:56.280 --> 41:59.249
Yes, okay, I enjoy it.

41:59.280 --> 42:01.748
But I'm not a detective, Mom.

42:01.780 --> 42:03.179
And I'm almost done
working with Sherlock,

42:03.220 --> 42:04.983
and then it's on
to another client.

42:05.020 --> 42:07.284
Will the next client
make you happy?

42:08.990 --> 42:13.029
People find their paths
in the strangest of ways.

42:14.900 --> 42:16.595
So sorry to interrupt.

42:16.630 --> 42:17.858
I've just, I've seen

42:17.900 --> 42:19.697
the most incredible thing
on the news.

42:19.730 --> 42:21.869
I'm quite sure
you'd want to see it.

42:21.900 --> 42:23.561
REPORTER: The police
are puzzled by the sudden

42:23.600 --> 42:25.101
and unexplained return

42:25.140 --> 42:27.700
of Vincent Van Gogh's
masterpiece, Piet.

42:27.740 --> 42:29.230
It was delivered
by courier to the head

42:29.280 --> 42:31.305
of the Aster Museum
of Modern Art.

42:31.340 --> 42:34.173
The NYPD is speculating
that the thief must have been

42:34.210 --> 42:35.609
suffering from
a guilty conscience,

42:35.650 --> 42:37.641
but the exact motive
for the return

42:37.680 --> 42:39.887
remains a mystery.

